  "prompt": "What are some of the best Soft Rock songs of all time?",
  "response": "Soft rock has been a beloved genre for decades, blending catchy melodies with soothing instrumentation and heartfelt lyrics. Here are some of the best soft rock songs of all time, spanning various eras and highlighting the genre's enduring appeal:\n\n1. **\"Sailing\" by Christopher Cross (1980)**\n   - Often hailed as the epitome of soft rock, this calming track won multiple Grammy Awards and remains a timeless favorite.\n\n2. **\"Hotel California\" by Eagles (1977)**\n   - A classic that blends rock elements with a softer edge, featuring memorable guitar solos and evocative lyrics.\n\n3. **\"Your Song\" by Elton John (1970)**\n   - A tender and sincere ballad that showcases Elton John's exceptional songwriting and vocal abilities.\n\n4. **\"Every Breath You Take\" by The Police (1983)**\n   - While sometimes interpreted as a darker song, its mellow melody and haunting lyrics make it a staple in soft rock.\n\n5. **\"Wonderful Tonight\" by Eric Clapton (1977)**\n   - A romantic ballad that highlights Clapton's smooth guitar work and heartfelt vocals.\n\n6. **\"Bridge Over Troubled Water\" by Simon & Garfunkel (1970)**\n   - An uplifting and soothing song that has become an anthem of comfort and support.\n\n7. **\"Africa\" by Toto (1982)**\n   - Featuring catchy hooks and rich harmonies, this song has enjoyed enduring popularity across generations.\n\n8. **\"Landslide\" by Fleetwood Mac (1975)**\n   - A reflective and emotional track that showcases Stevie Nicks' poignant songwriting.\n\n9. **\"I Want to Know What Love Is\" by Foreigner (1984)**\n   - A powerful ballad with soaring vocals and a memorable chorus that's become a soft rock classic.\n\n10. **\"More Than a Feeling\" by Boston (1976)**\n    - Known for its iconic guitar riffs and melodic structure, this song remains a favorite among rock and soft rock fans alike.\n\n11. **\"Sara\" by Fleetwood Mac (1979)**\n    - A beautifully arranged song with lush harmonies and introspective lyrics.\n\n12. **\"Time After Time\" by Cyndi Lauper (1983)**\n    - Although often classified under pop, its mellow vibe and soothing melody fit well within the soft rock realm.\n\n13. **\"Easy\" by Commodores (1977)**\n    - A laid-back track with soulful vocals and a smooth groove that's perfect for relaxed listening.\n\n14. **\"Babe\" by Styx (1979)**\n    - A heartfelt ballad that combines rock instrumentation with tender lyrics.\n\n15. **\"Angie\" by The Rolling Stones (1973)**\n    - A gentle, acoustic track that showcases a softer side of the iconic rock band.\n\n16. **\"Dreams\" by Fleetwood Mac (1977)**\n    - With its flowing melody and harmonious vocals, this song is a staple in the soft rock genre.\n\n17. **\"I Don't Want to Miss a Thing\" by Aerosmith (1998)**\n    - A powerful ballad that became synonymous with romantic sentiments, especially after its feature in the film *Armageddon*.\n\n18. **\"Patience\" by Guns N' Roses (1989)**\n    - An acoustic-driven song that highlights a more mellow and introspective side of the band.\n\n19. **\"Drive\" by The Cars (1984)**\n    - A synth-infused track with emotive lyrics and a smooth melody that defines 80s soft rock.\n\n20. **\"Smooth Operator\" by Sade (1984)**\n    - Blending elements of jazz and soft rock, this song is celebrated for its sleek production and Sade's sultry vocals.\n\nThese songs represent just a fraction of the rich catalog of soft rock music. Each has left a significant mark on the genre and continues to be cherished by fans around the world. Whether you're revisiting old favorites or discovering new ones, soft rock offers a diverse range of sounds and emotions to explore.",
